title: "Companion"
rating: 0.1
review {
  direction {
    director {
      name: "Drew Hancock"
    }
    rating: "TODO"
    comments: "The direction on a macroscale feels unique as the movie both feels genre-less as well as very visual; the direction on microscale is pretty good between the two leads as you can feel there is a good amount of chemistry between the two, but alright with the rest of the cast; storytelling is very visual as the director prefers to show rather than tell, especially in the flashbacks and action sequences; they build tension very well to make this movie uphold to its thriller/horror name"
  }
  acting {
    performance {
      actor {
        name: "Sophie Thatcher"
      }
      rating: "Pretty Good to Good"
      comments: "Really embodies the character as her character starts to build her emotions the more the movie goes on, have a good range by the end; really controls the scenes she is in as she really has established herself as a future scream queen; has good chemistry with Quaid as you really feel her character is a companion that cares about her 'lover'"
    }
    performance {
      actor {
        name: "Jack Quaid"
      }
      rating: "Pretty Good"
      comments: "Has strong charisma on screen and really is establishing himself as a film lead; shows a pretty good range of emotions; has good chemistry with Thatcher as he is one half of a very complicated relationship"
    }
    cast {
      rating: "Decent"
      comments: "Very standard background characters; hold their own, but don't do anything to really lift up the two leads"
    }
    rating: "Pretty Good"
  }
  story {
    writer {
      name: "Drew Hancock"
    }
    rating: "Pretty Good to Good"
    comments: "The concept is very unique as it very much feels like a 'Ex-Machina at home,' but at the same time stays original and unique with all it's twists and turns; the plot structure is pretty standard, but deviates a bit with all it's twists and turns; character writing is good for Iris as the character not only looks at the morality of AI, but explores female indepedence too"
  }
  screenplay {
    writer {
      name: "Drew Hancock"
    }
    rating: "Pretty Good"
    comments: "The dialogue is pretty lackluster and unnatural, but it does have good lines; the humor is a big element for this movie because it makes it feel very genre-less; the symbolism is strong as it uses a discussion on AI and this flawed relationship as a way to explore female indepdence; the foreshadowing is very good as the movie uses a lot of twists and turns to make it unique and interesting, but is still very full-circle through it's foreshadowing"
  }
